1386","1406":"1406","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","England":"England","Carnforth, Lancashire, England":"Carnforth, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hawkin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hawken  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hawkins","meanings":["English: variant of   Hawkin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name, with excrescent <i>-s</i>, from Hawkinge (Kent). The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Heafoc</i> or Old English <i>heafoc</i> ‘hawk’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>. This name has been assimilated to the patronymic surname in Devon from Sir John Hawkyns (1532–95), victor against the Spanish Armada (1588), who was a member of the Devon family of <i>Hawkins</i>, a branch of a Kentish family from the village of Hawkinge. They held land in Plymouth as long ago as 1480.","Irish: variant of   Haughn  ."]},{"name":"Hawken","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon):","from Middle English <i>Haw</i>, a rhyming pet form of <i>Raw</i> (Ralph), + the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. <i>Hawkyn</i> or <i>Haukyn</i> mean ‘young Ralph’. However, in 13th- and 14th-century handwriting <i>-u-</i> and <i>-n-</i> are often written identically, and some examples of <i>Haukyn</i> may therefore belong with   Hankin  . In <i>The Vision of William concerning Piers the Plowman</i> (written before 1387?) Langland named his fictional everyman figure ‘<i>Haukyn</i> the actyf man’, which strongly implies that in the late 14th century <i>Haukin</i> was a recognizable pet form of an everyday personal name, as <i>Ralph</i> was (see   Ralph  ). Compare   Haw   1 and   Dawkins  .","sometimes perhaps a variant of <b>Alkin</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i> and a post-1400 vocalization of <i>Halk-</i> to <i>Hawk-</i>. <i>Alkin</i> was a Middle English personal name, a pet form of names such as <i>Alan</i>, <i>Alexander</i>, and <i>Alice</i> + the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. Compare   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Haw","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Haw(e)</i> which, like <i>Daw(e)</i>, was probably a rhyming pet form of Middle English <i>Raw</i> (Ralph). Similar rhyming pet forms of other Anglo-Norman male personal names beginning with <i>R-</i> are found in <i>Hick</i> and <i>Dick</i> for <i>Rick</i> (Richard) and <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i> for <i>Rob(ert)</i>. See also   Hawkin  .","English: topographic name for someone who lived by an enclosure, from Middle English <i>hawe</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>haga</i> or Old Norse <i>hagi</i>). Compare   Haugh  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 何 and 賀, see   He   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":2,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":11,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":56,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margery Hawkin was born about 1326. She married Robert de Washington III in 1339, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died after 1386, in Lancashire, England."},"et":{"about 1326–after 1386":"umbes 1326–pärast 1386","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1340–1406":"1340–1406","1326–1386":"1326–1386","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1453":"1453","about 1326":"umbes 1326","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1320":"1320","after 1386":"pärast 1386","1406":"1406","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","England":"England","Carnforth, Lancashire, England":"Carnforth, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1326–after 1386":"noin 1326–1386 jälkeen","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1340–1406":"1340–1406","1326–1386":"1326–1386","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1453":"1453","about 1326":"noin 1326","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1320":"1320","after 1386":"1386 jälkeen","1406":"1406","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","England":"England","Carnforth, Lancashire, England":"Carnforth, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1326–after 1386":"environ 1326–après 1386","1320–1375":"1320–1375","1340–1406":"1340–1406","1326–1386":"1326–1386","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1453":"1453","about 1326":"environ 1326","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1320":"1320","after 1386":"après 1386","1406":"1406","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","England":"Angleterre","Carnforth, Lancashire, England":"Carnforth, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margery Hawkin est née environ 1326. Elle a épousé Robert de Washington